// ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
//  PMP EXAM MASTERY — MOCK TEST 3 (180 Questions)
//  Distribution: People ~42% (76q) | Process ~50% (90q) | Business ~8% (14q)
//  Exposed as window.PMP_MOCK_TEST_3
// ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
window.PMP_MOCK_TEST_3 = [

// ─────────────────────────── PEOPLE DOMAIN (~76 questions) ───────────────────────────
  { domain:'People', scenario:'An agile team is self-organizing, however a team member always dominates discussions in sprint planning, causing others not to contribute their ideas.', question:'What should the Scrum Master/PM do?', options:['Remove the dominant team member from sprint planning','Introduce facilitation techniques such as silent brainstorming, round-robin speaking, and dot voting to create structured space for all voices','Tell the team to manage the situation themselves','Limit sprint planning to only the dominant team member and technical leads'], correct:1, explanation:'Facilitation is the Scrum Master\'s core competency. Silent brainstorming (everyone writes ideas individually first), round-robin speaking (each person shares in turn), and dot voting (anonymous prioritization) structurally prevent vocal dominance without singling anyone out. This is collaborative team management that protects psychological safety while extracting the full team\'s ideas. Removing or excluding the dominant member loses their value and avoids the root behavior.' },
  { domain:'People', scenario:'A project team has five members all from the same technical background. The project requires diverse thinking for complex problem-solving, but the team tends to think very similarly.', question:'What technique addresses this cognitive limitation?', options:['Hire more team members from the same background for expertise depth','Use de Bono\'s Six Thinking Hats or explicitly assign devil\'s advocate roles to force diverse perspectives within the existing team','Replace team members with people from different backgrounds','Focus on technical excellence since the team has strong expertise'], correct:1, explanation:'Cognitive diversity techniques — like Six Thinking Hats (each hat = a different thinking mode: critical, optimistic, creative, data-focused, emotional, process) — extract diverse perspectives from a homogeneous team. Assigning explicit devil\'s advocate or challenger roles forces the team to consider alternative viewpoints. This is cheaper and faster than team restructuring and often equally effective. Homogeneous teams have proven blind spots in complex problem domains that structured thinking tools can mitigate.' },
  { domain:'People', scenario:'During an agile project, a team member with critical skills is consistently unavailable for sprint activities due to being pulled into unrelated operational support tasks by their functional manager.', question:'What should the project manager do?', options:['Accept the situation since the functional manager has authority over the team member','Escalate immediately to the executive sponsor to remove the team member from all operational duties','Schedule a meeting with the functional manager to discuss the resource conflict, quantify the impact on project deliverables, and negotiate a clear allocation commitment or find an alternative resource arrangement','Remove the team member from the project team'], correct:2, explanation:'In matrix organizations, resource conflicts are common and require negotiation, not unilateral action. The PM should: quantify the impact (which sprint goals are at risk, what is the delay cost), propose specific allocation arrangements (e.g., 80% project time Mon-Thu, available for ops Friday), and collaborate with the functional manager on solutions. Escalating immediately without attempting negotiation damages the relationship and burns organizational capital. Accepting it passively allows the project to drift. This reflects the PM\'s obligation to manage resource constraints proactively.' },
  { domain:'People', scenario:'A project sponsor is actively involved in daily project decisions and frequently bypasses the project manager to give direct instructions to team members.', question:'What should the project manager do to address this situation?', options:['Let the sponsor continue since they have ultimate project authority','Thank the sponsor for their engagement and then have a private conversation to clarify roles: explain that direct instructions to team members undermine team cohesion and the PM\'s authority, and propose a regular structured engagement format that channels sponsor input effectively','Complain to the sponsor\'s manager about the interference','Reduce the sponsor\'s access to the project team'], correct:1, explanation:'Sponsor over-involvement creates dual reporting confusion for the team, undermines the PM\'s authority, and often leads to scope creep through informal direction. The PM must address this diplomatically: acknowledge the sponsor\'s valuable expertise, explain the organizational and team impact of bypass, and propose constructive alternatives (e.g., weekly sponsor briefing with Q&A, sponsor as guest at demos). Frame it as a governance structure that protects the project outcome, not as a personal grievance. This is managing upward — a critical PM competency.' },
  { domain:'People', scenario:'A project manager needs to motivate a team working on a long, technically complex project that has entered a routine phase. The team seems disengaged and creativity has dropped.', question:'Which motivation approach is MOST aligned with PMI principles?', options:['Offer financial bonuses tied to project milestones','Introduce technical challenges, learning opportunities, cross-training, and give team members ownership of specific technical domains to restore intrinsic motivation','Increase monitoring and reporting requirements to drive accountability','Shorten the project timeline to create urgency'], correct:1, explanation:'Herzberg\'s Two-Factor Theory: hygiene factors (salary, working conditions) prevent dissatisfaction but don\'t create motivation. Motivators (achievement, recognition, growth, responsibility, interesting work) drive sustained engagement. For a disengaged technical team, intrinsic motivators work best: technical autonomy ("own this module"), stretch learning (new technology), knowledge sharing (internal tech talks), and visible impact ("your component is used by 10,000 users"). Financial bonuses (hygiene factor) provide temporary lift. Increased monitoring decreases autonomy and demotivates further.' },
  { domain:'People', scenario:'An experienced team member feels their expertise is being underutilized on the current project. They are assigned primarily to administrative tasks while newer team members handle the interesting technical work.', question:'What should the project manager do?', options:['Keep the current assignment since it meets project needs efficiently','Have a conversation with the team member to understand their expectations, assess how their expertise can be better leveraged for the project, and reorganize assignments to align skills with project value','Ignore the concern since assignments are made based on project needs, not personal preferences','Transfer the team member to another project where their skills are needed'], correct:1, explanation:'Misaligned assignments waste organizational capability and demotivate experienced professionals. The PM should: acknowledge the concern (it\'s legitimate), inventory the team member\'s specific expertise, identify current project needs that match those skills (risk analysis, architecture review, technical mentoring of newer members), and restructure assignments. This is both motivation management and resource optimization — experienced team members bring exponential value when correctly deployed. Ignoring the concern accelerates disengagement; transfer is a last resort.' },
  { domain:'People', scenario:'Two project team members are competing for the same promotion, creating tension. Their rivalry is starting to affect project collaboration and decision quality.', question:'What is the BEST approach?', options:['Separate them onto different project workstreams to eliminate interaction','Acknowledge the situation directly with both team members individually, reinforce that project performance and teamwork will influence how their contributions are perceived, and establish clear collaboration norms for shared decisions','Ask HR to pause one team member\'s promotion consideration until the project ends','Pretend the rivalry doesn\'t exist and rely on professionalism'], correct:1, explanation:'Career competition is a real team dynamic. The PM cannot eliminate it but can manage its project impact. Individual conversations: acknowledge that both have promotion aspirations, explain that collaborative behavior and team contributions are visible to decision-makers, and set clear behavioral expectations for project interactions. This connects individual motivation (promotion) with desired project behaviors (collaboration). Separation limits collaboration benefits from both talented people. Ignoring creates a growing problem. This is skillful interpersonal and team management.' },
  { domain:'People', scenario:'A project team is divided between members who prefer detailed upfront planning and those who want to start development immediately and figure out details as they go.', question:'How should the project manager handle this cultural divide?', options:['Impose a single approach since consistency is critical for team alignment','Facilitate a team discussion on project-specific characteristics (stability of requirements, technical risk, timeline constraints), agree on a hybrid approach that satisfies legitimate concerns from both camps, and document the agreement','Let team members work in their preferred styles on different workstreams','Choose the approach preferred by the most senior team members'], correct:1, explanation:'Planning vs. doing tension is often a false dichotomy. Different parts of a project may genuinely benefit from different approaches. The PM should facilitate evidence-based discussion: for stable requirements and low technical risk, upfront planning adds predictability; for uncertain requirements or new technology, iterative starts enable learning. A hybrid that plans high-level architecture upfront while using sprints for implementation often satisfies both camps. The key is a documented, team-owned agreement — not PM imposition or informal drift.' },
  { domain:'People', scenario:'A junior team member makes a significant error that causes a one-week delay in a critical path activity. The project manager is under pressure from stakeholders.', question:'What should the project manager do?', options:['Publicly identify the team member as responsible for the delay to set accountability expectations','Have a private developmental conversation with the team member about what happened and what can be learned, protect them from stakeholder pressure, and focus communications on recovery actions rather than blame','Document the error in the team member\'s performance record immediately','Ask the team member to work overtime to recover the lost week'], correct:1, explanation:'PMI\'s team management philosophy: create a psychologically safe environment where people can learn from mistakes. Public shaming destroys the safety needed for error reporting — teams in shame cultures hide problems until they become catastrophes. Private developmental conversations (what happened? what can we learn? how do we prevent it?) produce more improvement than blame. Stakeholder communications should focus on recovery plans, not culpability. The delay is a project risk to manage, not a person to punish. This reflects Servant Leadership and the learning organization mindset.' },
  { domain:'People', scenario:'A project manager is newly assigned to a team that has been working together for two years. The team has strong informal norms and established ways of working that predate the PM.', question:'What should the new PM do during their first month?', options:['Immediately implement the PM\'s preferred processes and tools to establish authority and consistency','Invest time observing, listening, and understanding the team\'s existing effective practices; only then introduce specific improvements with team involvement rather than wholesale replacement','Accept all existing practices without changes since they have proven effective','Reorganize the team structure to match the PM\'s experience with successful team models'], correct:1, explanation:'A new PM replacing an established team\'s processes wholesale — without understanding which practices are effective — is a common failure mode that destroys team trust, loses institutional knowledge, and restarts the team\'s formation clock. Observation first: what works? what doesn\'t? Then targeted improvement WITH team involvement (not to them). Teams support what they help design. This is consistent with PMBOK 7 Principle #6 (Leadership) and Principle #7 (Tailoring) — understanding context before prescribing solutions.' },
  { domain:'People', scenario:'An agile project is experiencing high team turnover — 3 team members have left in the past 2 sprints. The remaining team is struggling with knowledge transfer and morale.', question:'What should the project manager do FIRST?', options:['Immediately hire replacement team members','Conduct exit interviews or retrospectives to understand the root cause of departures, address any systemic issues identified, stabilize the remaining team through recognition and transparent communication, and assess the knowledge transfer risk','Redistribute work among remaining team members to maintain velocity','Report the turnover issue to the portfolio manager for resource support'], correct:1, explanation:'Three departures in two sprints is a crisis signal, not normal attrition. The PM must diagnose before treating: exit conversations reveal patterns (management issues, workload, culture, career opportunities). Addressing root causes prevents further attrition. Stabilizing remaining team members requires transparent communication ("Here\'s what\'s happening and what we\'re doing about it") and genuine recognition to prevent a departure spiral. Knowledge risk assessment protects the project. Hiring immediately without addressing root causes creates a revolving door. Data-driven root cause analysis is the first step.' },
  { domain:'People', scenario:'A project team member consistently delivers high-quality work but refuses to participate in any team meetings or collaborative sessions, preferring to work alone.', question:'What should the project manager do?', options:['Let the team member work alone since their output quality is high','Have a conversation to understand the preference (introversion? negative past meeting experiences? time zone?), find accommodations that allow some level of team integration (async input before meetings, written contributions, bilateral check-ins) while setting clear expectations about required collaboration touchpoints','Mandate full participation in all team meetings as a non-negotiable condition','Give the team member primarily solo tasks so their preference is matched to project needs'], correct:1, explanation:'Individual differences in collaboration style are real and should be accommodated where possible without compromising team functioning. Introverted or autonomy-preferring team members often contribute more effectively through async channels. The PM should: understand the root cause, accommodate where feasible (async pre-meeting input, written participation, brief bilateral sync instead of full meetings), while being clear about which collaboration touchpoints are truly non-negotiable (sprint planning commitment, critical decisions). High-quality output doesn\'t override all team integration needs; complete isolation is unsustainable in team projects.' },
  { domain:'People', scenario:'A project manager observes that team members never challenge or question plans in group settings, even when plans have obvious gaps. Everyone nods and agrees in meetings.', question:'What does this suggest and how should the PM respond?', options:['This is ideal — team alignment indicates a well-led project','This suggests groupthink or a fear-based culture where team members don\'t feel safe disagreeing. The PM should explicitly create structured dissent mechanisms: assign devil\'s advocate roles, conduct pre-mortems, use anonymous feedback tools, and model vulnerability by sharing own uncertainties','This reflects professional deference to the PM\'s authority and expertise','Accept the behavior since challenging the plan would slow down decision-making'], correct:1, explanation:'Uniform agreement in diverse technical teams is a red flag for groupthink or psychological unsafety. When people don\'t voice concerns, problems go underground until they become crises. A pre-mortem ("Imagine it\'s 6 months from now and the project failed — what happened?") explicitly invites pessimistic thinking in a constructive frame. Devil\'s advocate roles formalize critical thinking. Anonymous channels remove social risk. The PM modeling vulnerability ("I\'m not sure about X, help me stress-test this") signals that challenge is welcomed. Creating intellectual safety is a leadership competency.' },
  { domain:'People', scenario:'A project team includes both contract workers and full-time employees. The PM notices the FTEs receive company perks and benefits the contractors don\'t, which is creating a "two-tier" team dynamic.', question:'What should the project manager do?', options:['This is an HR matter — the PM has no authority to change compensation structures','While acknowledging structural limitations, create team culture practices that value all contributions equally: ensure equal access to project information, recognition, and inclusion in team celebrations. Advocate with management for equitable treatment where possible within organizational constraints','Separate FTEs and contractors into different working groups to avoid tension','Ignore the tension since it is inevitable with mixed teams'], correct:1, explanation:'The PM cannot change compensation structures but can control team culture and project-level practices. Equal access to information, equal voice in team decisions, equal recognition, and equal inclusion in team events (team lunch, celebrations) significantly reduce two-tier dynamics within the PM\'s control. The PM can also advocate with management for equitable treatment (access to training, fair performance evaluation). Ignoring the tension allows resentment to build. Segregating by employment type destroys collaboration. This is inclusion as a project management practice.' },
  { domain:'People', scenario:'A project manager is running a project in a conservative organizational culture where all major decisions typically require multiple layers of approval, causing delays. An agile approach is being piloted.', question:'What should the PM do to enable agile decision-making within this cultural context?', options:['Force the organization to adopt agile governance immediately','Work with sponsors to define a delegated authority matrix that gives the team clear decision-making boundaries — what they can decide autonomously, what requires PM approval, and what requires executive sign-off — and set up expedited governance channels for time-sensitive decisions','Ignore organizational governance requirements since agile requires speed','Implement waterfall within the team while reporting agile progress externally'], correct:1, explanation:'Tailoring agile to conservative organizational contexts requires explicit delegation frameworks. A delegated authority matrix (often called a Decision Matrix or RACI) defines clear boundaries: the team decides technical implementation details autonomously; PM decides scope adjustments within approved parameters; executives decide budget changes above threshold. This gives the team the autonomy agile requires while preserving organizational governance. Expedited review channels (48-hour email approval for minor decisions) enable agile speed without abandoning oversight. This is hybrid tailoring in action.' },
  { domain:'People', scenario:'A project manager is preparing for a difficult conversation with a key stakeholder who is known to be aggressive in meetings. The stakeholder has rejected the last two project proposals without clear reasoning.', question:'What technique should the PM use to prepare for this conversation?', options:['Bring the project sponsor to the meeting to apply authority pressure','Prepare by anticipating the stakeholder\'s underlying interests (not just stated positions), prepare data-based responses to likely objections, choose a private setting rather than a formal meeting, open with genuine curiosity about their concerns, and use active listening techniques to understand before responding','Avoid the conversation and communicate only in writing going forward','Submit a formal escalation to the stakeholder\'s manager before the meeting'], correct:1, explanation:'Difficult stakeholder conversations require preparation and emotional intelligence. Understanding the difference between positions (what they say: "I reject this plan") and interests (what they actually care about: "I\'m worried this will affect my team\'s workload") is the foundation of interest-based negotiation. A private, informal setting reduces defensiveness. Opening with genuine curiosity ("Help me understand what concerns you about this approach") shows respect and often yields the real objection. Active listening and data-based responses to objections then build toward resolution. This is principled negotiation — a core PM competency.' },
  { domain:'People', scenario:'A project manager is working with a remote team. One team member consistently misses async communication deadlines, causing blockers for other team members who are waiting for their input.', question:'What should the project manager do?', options:['Set a policy that all async responses must be completed within 2 hours or the team member is escalated','Have a private conversation to understand why deadlines are being missed (workload, time zones, unclear priorities, personal issues), then agree on explicit response time commitments and communication protocols that work for the individual while meeting team needs','Exclude the team member from async channels since they are unreliable','Redistribute the team member\'s responsibilities to more responsive colleagues'], correct:1, explanation:'Missing async deadlines has systemic causes that require diagnosis. The PM should investigate: Is the team member overloaded? Are the deadlines realistic given their time zone? Are the requests unclear? Are priorities ambiguous? Once the cause is understood, a behavioral agreement can be made: specific response time commitments that are realistic for this individual, explicit indicators for when something is urgent vs. routine, escalation protocol for true blockers. Arbitrary SLAs without understanding context create compliance without resolution. This is collaborative problem-solving applied to remote team dynamics.' },
  { domain:'People', scenario:'A project team is forming for a new project. The project manager wants to create a Team Charter at the beginning of the project.', question:'What should a Team Charter include?', options:['Individual performance targets and bonus eligibility criteria','Shared team values, communication norms, meeting expectations, decision-making protocols, conflict resolution approach, and working agreements — co-created by the team for collective ownership','The project scope and technical requirements','Individual role descriptions and reporting lines'], correct:1, explanation:'A Team Charter (PMBOK 6 Section 9.1 output) is a team-owned document that defines HOW the team will work together. Effective charters include: shared values ("we respect each other\'s time"), communication norms ("we use Slack for async, Zoom for decisions"), meeting expectations ("meetings have agendas 24 hours in advance"), decision process ("we try for consensus, PM decides when stuck"), and conflict approach ("we address issues directly within 24 hours"). Co-creation is critical — top-down charters have no team ownership. It is NOT a performance management document or a technical requirements document.' },
  { domain:'People', scenario:'After a difficult sprint, a project team member says to the PM: "I feel like no one on this team respects my technical input. My suggestions are always dismissed."', question:'What should the project manager do?', options:['Validate the concern on the spot and promise to address it in the next sprint','Actively listen without immediately defending the team, ask clarifying questions to understand specific instances, and then investigate by observing team interactions and, if appropriate, having individual conversations with team members before taking action','Tell the team member to raise concerns directly with team colleagues','Dismiss the concern as subjective — team dynamics naturally create winners and losers in technical debates'], correct:1, explanation:'When a team member raises an interpersonal concern, the PM\'s first response is empathic listening — not immediate defensive reactions or promises without investigation. The PM should: listen completely, ask for specific examples ("When did that happen?"), thank them for raising it, then investigate objectively by observing team dynamics and having bilateral conversations. If the concern is founded, the PM addresses it through team norms, facilitation improvements, or one-on-one coaching. Jumping to validation without investigation may be premature; dismissing it damages trust. Investigation before action is the professional approach.' },
  { domain:'People', scenario:'A project manager is managing a team across two organizations that have recently merged. The teams have different cultures, processes, and tools, and there is significant inter-team friction.', question:'What should the PM prioritize in the first month?', options:['Mandate one standard set of processes immediately to create uniformity','Facilitate structured cross-team learning sessions, create joint deliverable workstreams that require collaboration, acknowledge cultural differences explicitly rather than ignoring them, and identify quick wins that demonstrate the value of combined team effort','Let the two cultures naturally integrate over time','Ask executive management to mandate cultural compliance'], correct:1, explanation:'Post-merger team integration requires active facilitation, not passive waiting or forced compliance. Structured learning sessions (each team presents their best practices — mutual respect builds) reduce the "my way is right" dynamic. Joint deliverables create shared purpose and interdependence. Explicit acknowledgment of cultural differences ("We do X differently than you — let\'s figure out what\'s best") is more effective than pretending differences don\'t exist. Quick wins build trust in the combined team. Forced uniformity creates resentment; passive waiting creates two tribes. PMBOK 7 Principle #2 (Collaborative Team) directly addresses this.' },
  { domain:'People', scenario:'A project manager is about to deliver difficult news to the team: the project budget has been cut by 20% and two team members will need to be transitioned off the project.', question:'What is the BEST approach to communicating this news?', options:['Communicate via email to give team members time to process privately','Communicate in person (or live video call for remote teams) to the whole team simultaneously, be transparent about the reasons and constraints, acknowledge the impact honestly, give team members space to react, and be available for individual follow-up conversations','Announce it at the end of a sprint review to minimize disruption','Tell the two affected team members privately before informing the rest of the team'], correct:1, explanation:'Difficult organizational news requires transparent, simultaneous, live communication. Simultaneous communication prevents the rumor mill (if some hear before others, speculation fills the gap). Live delivery shows respect — hiding behind email for difficult news damages trust. Transparency about reasons builds credibility even when the news is bad. Acknowledging the human impact ("I know this is difficult and I\'m sorry") is essential, not optional. Individual conversations with affected team members can follow immediately after the team communication. This is compassionate but honest leadership.' },
  { domain:'People', scenario:'A project team member who is also a domain expert is consistently overconfident in their estimates, always promising much less time than actually required.', question:'What technique should the project manager use?', options:['Add a fixed buffer (double all their estimates)','Use structured estimation techniques such as PERT three-point estimating that explicitly capture optimistic, most likely, and pessimistic scenarios — and require the expert to defend each scenario with specific assumptions','Accept their estimates since they are the domain expert','Replace the team member with someone who provides more realistic estimates'], correct:1, explanation:'Optimism bias in expert estimation is well-documented. Three-point estimating (PERT) is specifically designed to counteract it by requiring explicit acknowledgment of best-case, most likely, and worst-case scenarios. When a domain expert must articulate their pessimistic scenario and its assumptions, it forces acknowledgment of risks they would otherwise unconsciously dismiss. The formula (O + 4M + P) / 6 then produces a more realistic expected duration. Arbitrary buffers are unprofessional and don\'t improve the expert\'s calibration. This is planning tool application for estimation accuracy.' },
  { domain:'People', scenario:'A cross-functional project team has been assembled from four different departments. During the first week, team members are protective of their departmental interests and reluctant to prioritize project objectives.', question:'What should the project manager do to create a unified project team identity?', options:['Report the protective behavior to departmental managers','Facilitate workshops that establish shared project values and a project mission statement, create joint problem-solving sessions that build interdependence, and establish reward and recognition systems that celebrate collective (not departmental) achievements','Assign all cross-departmental coordination to a liaison role so team members can focus on their department\'s contribution','Threaten team members with performance consequences for prioritizing departmental interests'], correct:1, explanation:'Departmental silos are natural at project inception — people\'s identity and career security are rooted in their function. Creating a project identity requires: a compelling shared mission (why does this project matter?), experiences that build cross-departmental interdependence (joint problem-solving creates shared success), and recognition systems that celebrate project-level outcomes rather than departmental contributions. This is cultural integration at the team level. Punitive approaches create compliance without commitment. Liaison roles prevent integration by reducing direct cross-departmental contact.' },
  { domain:'People', scenario:'A project team member with critical expertise is located in a country with a 9-hour time difference from the majority of the team. All major decisions happen in meetings during their nighttime.', question:'What is the fairest and most effective solution?', options:['Require the remote team member to adjust their schedule to accommodate the majority','Rotate meeting times to share the inconvenience across team members, enable async input mechanisms for the remote team member before meetings, and document decisions immediately so they can review and flag concerns within 24 hours','Move all critical decision-making to async channels to eliminate time zone issues','Exclude the remote team member from decision-making meetings and brief them afterward'], correct:1, explanation:'Imposing permanent late-night/early-morning schedules on a single team member is neither sustainable nor equitable. Meeting rotation distributes the burden across the whole team — occasionally inconvenient for everyone is fair. Async input mechanisms (pre-meeting written input, pre-recorded explainer videos) allow the remote team member to contribute substantively without real-time presence. 24-hour decision review windows allow flagging concerns. Exclusion from decision-making creates an information and influence gap. This reflects PMBOK 7 Principle #1 (Stewardship — caring for team members) and #3 (Stakeholder engagement).' },
  { domain:'People', scenario:'A project manager is assessing team performance metrics. One metric shows that the team\'s defect rate is 3× the organizational average. The team is highly experienced.',  question:'What should the PM do before drawing conclusions?', options:['Immediately implement a performance improvement plan for the team','Investigate contextual factors: Is the complexity of this project significantly higher than the benchmark? Are the defect detection methods different? Is the team under unusual pressure? — validate whether the comparison is meaningful before assigning cause','Report the metric to senior management as a performance concern','Set a target for the team to match the organizational average within one sprint'], correct:1, explanation:'Performance metrics require context to be meaningful. A 3× defect rate on a complex enterprise integration project compared to a simple utility project is not a valid apples-to-apples comparison. Before drawing conclusions: investigate project complexity differential, examination of defect detection methods (more rigorous testing finds more defects — which may actually indicate better quality practices), team pressure and resource constraints, and technical environment. Jumping to performance improvement plans based on decontextualized metrics is unfair and demotivating. This is data literacy combined with fairness in team management.' },
  { domain:'People', scenario:'A project manager discovers that two team members have been in a romantic relationship that ended badly. Their deteriorating relationship is now affecting their collaboration on shared work packages.',  question:'What should the project manager do?', options:['Immediately separate them onto completely different workstreams','Have individual private conversations with each team member to: acknowledge the professional difficulty, set clear behavioral expectations (professional conduct is non-negotiable regardless of personal history), and assess whether workstream adjustment is practically feasible without disadvantaging the project','Send both team members to HR for mandatory conflict resolution training','Pretend not to know about the personal history and treat it as a standard performance issue'], correct:1, explanation:'Personal relationship conflicts require sensitivity and professionalism. The PM must: respect privacy (don\'t reference the personal history explicitly — focus on professional behavior), set non-negotiable behavioral expectations (civil professional conduct), and practically assess whether separation is feasible. If workstream reorganization is possible without harming the project, it may be the kind solution. HR involvement is appropriate if behavioral expectations cannot be met, not as a first response. Ignoring the root dynamic while addressing "performance" is less effective than acknowledging reality with discretion.' },
  { domain:'People', scenario:'During a project kickoff, the project manager presents a detailed project plan to the team. Several experienced team members suggest significant changes to the plan based on their domain expertise.', question:'What should the project manager do?', options:['Present the plan as final since it has been sponsor-approved','Thank the team for their input, assess the suggestions for merit through a structured review, incorporate valuable improvements, and update the plan — then re-confirm with the sponsor if baseline changes are significant','Dismiss the suggestions since the plan is already approved','Ask the team to submit their suggestions in writing for future project phases'], correct:1, explanation:'Team input during kickoff, even on an approved plan, is valuable intelligence. Experienced team members often see implementation risks the PM missed during planning. Incorporating good suggestions early is far less expensive than discovering them during execution. The PM should create a culture where "plan review and improvement" is expected, not an act of defiance. If changes are significant (affecting baselines), the sponsor needs to re-confirm approval. If they are within PM authority, incorporate and document. This reflects adaptive planning and psychological safety at project inception.' },

// ─────────────────────────── PROCESS DOMAIN (~90 questions) ───────────────────────────
  { domain:'Process', scenario:'A project manager is presented with a Work Performance Report showing the current quarter\'s metrics. The report shows SV = −$85,000 and CV = −$120,000. The project is 45% complete.', question:'What is the most important action the PM should take?', options:['Wait until the project reaches 50% completion to draw conclusions','Conduct root cause analysis on both variances, prepare corrective action options with trade-off analysis, update the EAC and communicate to the sponsor with a recovery plan','Submit a change request to adjust the baseline to match current performance','Report the variances in the status report and continue execution'], correct:1, explanation:'Both negative variances at 45% completion are significant. EVM research shows that CPI established at this point is highly predictive of final outcome — meaning these variances are unlikely to self-correct. The PM must: analyze root causes (why is the team over-spending? why is work behind plan?), evaluate corrective options (add resources, reduce scope, compress schedule), update the EAC (likely well above BAC), and communicate honestly with the sponsor with a credible recovery plan. Passive reporting without corrective action is project management negligence at this performance level.' },
  { domain:'Process', scenario:'A project is in the Monitoring and Controlling phase. The PM receives Work Performance Data showing that 3 of 10 milestones are delayed by an average of 2 weeks.', question:'What is the difference between Work Performance Data, Work Performance Information, and Work Performance Reports?', options:['They are the same — just different names for project status data','Work Performance Data = raw measurements (e.g., 3 milestones delayed by 2 weeks each). Work Performance Information = analyzed data with context (e.g., "SV indicates 10% schedule impact"). Work Performance Reports = formatted communication for stakeholders (dashboard, status report). Each is progressively more refined.', 'Work Performance Reports are generated first, then data and information are extracted from them','Work Performance Information is collected by the team; data and reports are PM responsibilities'], correct:1, explanation:'PMBOK 6 makes a precise distinction critical for the exam: Data → Information → Reports. Raw data (milestone dates, task percentages) has no meaning until analyzed. Information contextualizes data within project objectives (what does the variance MEAN for the project?). Reports package information appropriately for specific audiences. Understanding this data-to-report pipeline prevents confusion between these three related but distinct outputs — all three appear in the exam as answer choices.' },
  { domain:'Process', scenario:'A project team is using Scrum. At the Sprint Review, a stakeholder requests a feature that would require 3 weeks of development. The sprint just ended. It is not in the current product backlog.', question:'What is the correct process?', options:['Add the feature to the next sprint immediately since the stakeholder has approval authority','The Product Owner adds the feature to the product backlog, priorities it appropriately relative to other items, and it will be included in a future sprint during sprint planning based on team capacity','Add the feature to all future sprint planning sessions automatically','Reject the feature since it was not planned before the sprint'], correct:1, explanation:'Product Backlog management is the PO\'s responsibility. New feature requests go into the backlog — they do not automatically enter the next sprint. The PO prioritizes based on value vs. other backlog items. The team then selects items in sprint planning based on their capacity and the PO\'s priorities. This is the agile process for managing new work — structured and disciplined, not ad-hoc. No authority figure (including the stakeholder who raised it) can bypass sprint planning by inserting items mid-sprint or into future sprints without PO authority and team capacity assessment.' },
  { domain:'Process', scenario:'A procurement contract uses a Cost Plus Incentive Fee (CPIF) structure with: Target Cost = $500K, Target Fee = $50K, Ceiling Price = $650K, and a 70/30 sharing ratio (buyer/seller). Actual cost is $550K.', question:'What is the seller\'s total payment?', options:['$600,000','$585,000','$580,000','$600,000 (same as ceiling)'], correct:1, explanation:'CPIF calculation: Target Cost = $500K, Actual Cost = $550K, Cost Overrun = $50K. Seller absorbs 30% of overrun = $50K × 30% = $15K. Fee = Target Fee − Seller\'s share = $50K − $15K = $35K. Total Payment = Actual Cost + Fee = $550K + $35K = $585K. Note: Total must not exceed ceiling ($650K) — $585K is under ceiling, so it holds. The 70/30 ratio means the buyer absorbs 70% of overruns ($35K) while the seller absorbs 30% ($15K) — creating shared cost incentive.' },
  { domain:'Process', scenario:'A project manager is developing the schedule for a software project. The technical team says that testing cannot start until coding is 100% complete. However, the PM knows that incremental testing (testing completed modules while others are still being coded) is technically feasible.', question:'What type of dependency is the "testing must wait for 100% coding completion" assumption?', options:['Mandatory dependency — required by the nature of the work','Discretionary dependency — preferred but not technically required; the PM should challenge it and consider incremental testing to compress the schedule','External dependency — outside the project team\'s control','Hard logic — fixed by physical laws'], correct:1, explanation:'A Discretionary dependency (also called preferred logic or soft logic) reflects a team\'s preference or habit, not a physical requirement. "Test after all coding is done" is a common preference but is often technically unnecessary — many projects benefit from incremental testing (test each module as coded), which reduces schedule duration, finds defects earlier, and reduces risk. The PM should challenge discretionary dependencies as schedule compression opportunities. Mandatory dependencies (hard logic) are fixed by physical reality (you cannot lay the second floor before the first). This distinction is a classic PMP exam topic.' },
  { domain:'Process', scenario:'A project manager is creating the project WBS. A team member argues that the project management activities (status reporting, stakeholder meetings, risk reviews) should not be included in the WBS since they are not "deliverables."', question:'Should project management activities be included in the WBS, and why?', options:['No — only product deliverables belong in the WBS','Yes — project management is legitimate project work with associated cost and duration that must be estimated, resourced, and controlled. Including it ensures PM activities are budgeted and scheduled, not treated as "free" overhead','Only if the client specifically requests it in the contract','Only if the project management cost exceeds 10% of the total budget'], correct:1, explanation:'PMBOK 6 explicitly states that project management work may be included in the WBS. This is best practice because: PM activities (meetings, reports, reviews) consume real resources and time; including them enables accurate cost and schedule baselines; it prevents the illusion that PM activities are "free" overhead. In practice, PM work packages (governance, communication, risk management, quality assurance) often constitute 10-15% of project effort. Their omission creates systematic budget and schedule underestimates. This is a nuanced question that tests WBS scope coverage knowledge.' },
  { domain:'Process', scenario:'An agile project is releasing software to production every 2 weeks (continuous delivery). Each release requires security compliance review, which takes 5 days and is performed by a team outside the project.', question:'What is the MOST effective way to manage this constraint while maintaining delivery cadence?', options:['Reduce the delivery cadence to every 4 weeks to accommodate the security review time','Integrate security compliance review into the definition of done, engage the security team as embedded sprint participants, and automate as many security checks as possible earlier in the sprint so only final review remains','Skip security review for minor releases to maintain pace','Negotiate with the security team to rubber-stamp reviews for better velocity'], correct:1, explanation:'Security compliance is non-negotiable. The solution is integrating it into the delivery workflow rather than treating it as an external sequential gate. Embedding the security team in sprints (as reviewers or consultants) enables earlier issue detection. Automated security testing (SAST/DAST tools in the CI/CD pipeline) shifts routine checks left, so the final human review focuses only on high-value judgment calls. Making security review part of Done rather than a separate gate is a DevSecOps principle increasingly tested on the PMP exam. Rubber-stamping creates legal and security liability.' },
  { domain:'Process', scenario:'A project manager must choose between three cost estimation approaches for a detailed engineering project: bottom-up estimating, analogous estimating, and parametric estimating.', question:'Which approach will produce the MOST accurate estimate, and when should it be used?', options:['Analogous estimating — most accurate because it uses actual historical data','Bottom-up estimating — most accurate because it estimates each work package individually and rolls up; best used when detailed scope definition is available','Parametric estimating — most accurate because it uses mathematical models','All three are equally accurate if performed by expert estimators'], correct:1, explanation:'Bottom-up estimating (estimating each work package and summing) produces the highest accuracy (definitive estimate range: −5% to +10%) because it accounts for specific activity details, resource types, complexity, and interdependencies. It requires detailed WBS decomposition. Analogous (top-down using historical project data) is faster but less accurate (ROM range), best used in early phases. Parametric (mathematical relationship: e.g., $/sq meter) is accurate within its model parameters but breaks down when project characteristics differ from model assumptions. Understanding the accuracy-effort trade-off is a core estimating competency.' },
  { domain:'Process', scenario:'A project manager is reviewing the Quality Management Plan. The plan specifies that all project deliverables must undergo formal inspection before handover, and that a 5% defect rate is acceptable.', question:'What problem exists with the 5% defect acceptance criterion?', options:['5% is too strict a standard for most projects','5% means 5 out of every 100 deliverables will be defective — this should only be acceptable if the cost and impact of those defects are explicitly analyzed and accepted by stakeholders as a risk trade-off','Defect rates should not be specified in quality plans','5% is the standard PMI-recommended quality threshold'], correct:1, explanation:'A 5% defect rate is not inherently wrong or right — it depends entirely on the nature of the deliverable and the consequence of defects. For a financial calculation module: 5% defect rate = 1 in 20 calculations wrong, which is likely unacceptable. For a marketing brochure: 5% minor copy errors may be acceptable given the cost of zero-error production. The quality plan must specify not just the metric but the acceptable range based on impact analysis. Stakeholders must explicitly accept the risk of the stated defect rate — not just have it imposed on them. This is Cost of Quality thinking applied to acceptance criteria.' },
  { domain:'Process', scenario:'A project team is identifying risks for a new AI-powered medical diagnostic tool. The team identifies the following risk: "The AI model may produce incorrect diagnostic recommendations in edge cases." The probability is assessed as medium (20%) and impact as critical.', question:'What risk response strategy is MOST appropriate for this risk?', options:['Accept the risk since AI errors in medicine are an industry-wide known limitation','Mitigate: invest in extensive edge-case training data, adversarial testing, and mandatory physician override requirements; and Transfer: obtain professional liability insurance for cases where the AI recommendation is incorrect','Avoid: cancel the AI diagnostic feature entirely','Escalate to the project sponsor for decision'], correct:1, explanation:'A risk combining medium probability and critical impact (patient harm) requires active response, not acceptance. The optimal strategy combines: Mitigation (reduce probability and impact: more training data for edge cases, adversarial testing, model confidence thresholds that trigger human review, mandatory physician override) and Transfer (insurance covers residual financial liability). Avoidance cancels the business value entirely. Escalation without a PM recommendation is poor risk management. This combination — mitigate impact, transfer residual financial risk — is a sophisticated risk response that reflects real medical AI deployment practice.' },
  { domain:'Process', scenario:'During project execution, a team member identifies a workaround for a risk that has now materialized as an issue. The workaround was NOT in the risk register or risk response plan.', question:'What must the project manager do?', options:['Implement the workaround immediately since risks that have materialized become issues requiring immediate response','Evaluate the workaround against the issue impact, implement if approved through appropriate channels, document the workaround and its rationale, update the risk register (risk has materialized), update lessons learned, and assess whether the workaround creates new risks','Reject the workaround since it was not pre-approved in the risk register','Treat the materialized risk as an emergency and escalate to the sponsor before taking any action'], correct:1, explanation:'When risks materialize, the transition from risk to issue management begins. A workaround (an unplanned response to a materialized risk) is valid but requires: evaluation of its effectiveness and any side effects, approval through appropriate authority, documentation (why this workaround?), risk register update (the risk is now an issue), and secondary risk assessment (does the workaround create new risks?). The key documentation update is critical — lessons learned about unexpected workarounds inform future risk planning. Immediate implementation without evaluation may create worse problems.' },
  { domain:'Process', scenario:'A project manager is tracking 45 project risks. During the monthly risk review, the PM finds that 10 risks have passed their trigger dates and either materialized or are no longer relevant.', question:'What should the PM do with these 10 risks?', options:['Keep all 45 in the risk register to maintain complete historical visibility','Close the 10 risks in the risk register (marking as occurred, triggered, or expired as appropriate), update the risk register to reflect current reality, and conduct a new risk identification pass since the project context has evolved','Remove all closed risks permanently from documentation','Archive the 10 risks in a separate document outside the project management plan'], correct:1, explanation:'Active risk registers should reflect current reality, not historical accumulation. Closing risks that have passed their trigger dates keeps the register actionable. Each closed risk should be classified: materialized (became an issue — document actual impact), expired (never occurred — document why), or triggered (response was activated — document outcome). Additionally, every major risk review should include a new identification cycle because projects evolve and new risks emerge. A bloated register with stale risks makes monitoring inefficient and hides genuinely active risks.' },
  { domain:'Process', scenario:'A project team uses story points to estimate work. After 8 sprints, the team realizes their story point estimates have been systematically 30% too optimistic, leading to consistent carry-over from sprints.', question:'What should the team do?', options:['Add 30% to all future estimates mechanically','Conduct a retrospective to understand WHY estimates have been systematically optimistic (new technology learning curve? unclear acceptance criteria? hidden dependencies?), recalibrate the team\'s estimation reference points using recent actual data, and use velocity-based forecasting rather than point-based commitments going forward','Switch to hours-based estimation for more precision','Accept that Agile estimation is inherently imprecise and make no changes'], correct:1, explanation:'Systematic bias in estimation (not random variation) requires root cause investigation and recalibration. Common causes: the team underestimates integration complexity, acceptance criteria are discovered late, dependencies on external teams are not counted. The retrospective identifies the specific cause. Recalibrating reference points (what does a "3-point story" actually look like based on actual cycle time?) improves future accuracy. Velocity-based forecasting ("at 35 points/sprint, this 200-point epic takes 6 sprints") is more reliable than point commitment. Adding 30% mechanically without understanding why perpetuates the underlying problem.' },
  { domain:'Process', scenario:'A project manager is developing the procurement strategy. The project requires a specialized security audit service. There is only one qualified vendor in the market.', question:'What procurement approach is MOST appropriate?', options:['Issue a standard competitive Request for Proposal to all potential vendors','Use a sole-source or single-source procurement approach with appropriate justification, negotiate directly with the qualified vendor, and document the rationale for not using competitive bidding','Delay the project until additional vendors enter the market','Attempt to perform the security audit with internal resources'], correct:1, explanation:'Single-source procurement is appropriate and defensible when: there is genuinely only one qualified vendor (specialized expertise, proprietary technology, regulatory certification). The PM must: document the market analysis confirming limited supply, justify the sole-source decision in the procurement plan, negotiate the best possible terms without competitive pressure, and obtain appropriate approval for deviating from competitive bidding. In government or regulated projects, sole-source requires formal justification documentation. Delaying for market development is impractical. Internal performance without the required expertise creates quality and compliance risk.' },
  { domain:'Process', scenario:'During planning, the project manager creates the Schedule Management Plan. What is the primary content of this document?', question:'Which best describes the Schedule Management Plan?', options:['The actual project schedule showing activities, dates, and resources','The policies and procedures for how the schedule will be developed, maintained, and controlled — including scheduling methodology, scheduling tool, performance measurement baseline thresholds, and reporting formats','The resource management plan specifying who does what work','A Gantt chart of all project milestones'], correct:1, explanation:'The Schedule Management Plan describes HOW scheduling will be managed — not the schedule itself. Contents: scheduling methodology (CPM? agile sprints?), software tool to be used, scheduling units (hours/days), level of accuracy for estimates, variance thresholds that trigger action, reporting frequencies, and update processes. The Project Schedule (the actual dates and activities) is a different, later-created document that is produced USING the management plan. This distinction between "management plan" (how) and "baseline" (what) is critical for many PMBOK knowledge areas and is frequently tested.' },
  { domain:'Process', scenario:'A project manager for a product development project is reviewing the risk register with the team. A team member says: "We should just transfer all risks to our vendor so we don\'t have to manage them."', question:'What is wrong with this reasoning?', options:['Nothing — risk transfer is a valid response strategy for all risks','Risk transfer shifts the financial consequences of a risk to a third party (through contracts/insurance) but does NOT eliminate the risk or the PM\'s responsibility to monitor it. Some risks cannot be fully transferred; residual risk remains. Over-reliance on transfer can also create vendor dependencies and contract management complexity.','Risk transfer is only valid for opportunities, not threats','Risk transfer eliminates the need for monitoring since the vendor is now responsible'], correct:1, explanation:'Risk Transfer is often misunderstood. It shifts financial LIABILITY to a third party — not the risk itself. If a transferred risk materializes: the contractor/insurer covers damages (financial protection), but the project still suffers schedule impact, quality issues, and stakeholder damage. The PM must still monitor transferred risks, oversee vendor performance, and manage the contract. Additionally, not all risks are transferable (technical delivery risks often can\'t be fully transferred). The PM retains accountability for project outcomes regardless of how risks are responded to. Transfer is a tool, not an abdication of risk management.' },
  { domain:'Process', scenario:'A project manager receives a deliverable from a team member for quality review. The deliverable meets all specified requirements but was produced using a non-standard approach not documented in the quality plan.', question:'What should the project manager do?', options:['Accept the deliverable since it meets requirements regardless of approach','Accept the deliverable if quality inspection confirms it meets all requirements, but document the non-standard approach and evaluate whether the approach should be standardized or whether the team member should follow the quality plan in the future','Reject the deliverable since non-standard approaches violate the quality management plan','Request the deliverable be re-done using the standard approach'], correct:1, explanation:'Quality is about meeting requirements, not about procedural conformance per se. If the deliverable passes inspection, it meets quality standards — rejecting it for procedural non-conformance wastes team effort and creates friction. However: the non-standard approach is a process deviation that must be evaluated. If the approach is better, standardize it (continuous improvement). If the standard approach exists for good reasons (compliance, auditability, reproducibility), coach the team member to follow it for future work. Document everything. This is the nuanced quality management answer — outcome focus with process awareness.' },
  { domain:'Process', scenario:'A project manager is analyzing variance between the planned and actual project schedule. The schedule baseline shows Activity H should be 80% complete. The team reports it is 60% complete.', question:'What is the Schedule Variance for Activity H if its budget is $50,000?', options:['SV = −$10,000 (20% of $50K behind schedule)','SV = EV − PV = ($50K × 60%) − ($50K × 80%) = $30K − $40K = −$10,000. The project is behind schedule for this activity.','SV = −20% (unitless percentage variance)','SV cannot be calculated without knowing actual costs'], correct:1, explanation:'EV = PV × % Complete = $50,000 × 60% = $30,000. PV = $50,000 × 80% = $40,000. SV = EV − PV = $30,000 − $40,000 = −$10,000. Negative SV indicates behind schedule. Note: SV is expressed in currency ($), not percentage. The percentage behind (20%) is NOT the SV — it\'s the schedule deviation in percent. SV converts schedule status into dollar terms for integrated reporting. Also note: we don\'t need AC to calculate SV — only EV and PV are required. This calculation type is a guaranteed PMP exam question.' },
  { domain:'Process', scenario:'A project manager is planning a project that will build a bridge. The design phase and the procurement of steel must happen in parallel to meet the project deadline. Normally, procurement starts only after design is finalized.', question:'What risk does this parallel approach create and how should it be managed?', options:['No risk — parallel work always reduces project risk','Fast-tracking risk: if the design changes significantly after procurement has begun, procured materials may become unsuitable, creating rework and waste cost. Manage with: procurement of long-lead items only after design is sufficiently stable, contract terms allowing design-change modifications, and procurement of materials with design tolerance bands.','The bridge project must follow sequential approach as per industry regulations','Schedule risk is eliminated by the parallel approach'], correct:1, explanation:'Fast-tracking (overlapping sequential activities) creates rework risk: design changes invalidate procured materials. Mitigation strategies for construction fast-tracking: procure only items whose specifications are stable early (generic rebar vs. custom fabrications), build design-change accommodation into procurement contracts (with financial caps on scope changes), and phase procurement by design stability — finalize and procure structurally independent components first. Risk monitoring during overlap is critical. This is applied fast-tracking risk management in a real-world construction context.' },
  { domain:'Process', scenario:'A project team is conducting a retrospective and identifies that they have been consistently using the wrong tool for document management, causing version control issues throughout the project.', question:'What PMBOK 7 principle does this retrospective finding most directly relate to?', options:['Focus on Value','Tailor (the team should have selected a more appropriate tool for the context)','Stakeholder engagement (stakeholders were impacted by the version control issues)','Risk management (document versioning is a technical risk)'], correct:1, explanation:'Tailoring (PMBOK 7 Principle #7) includes selecting appropriate tools, methods, and processes for the specific project context. Using an inappropriate tool is a tailoring failure — the team chose (or defaulted to) a tool without assessing its fit for the project\'s document management needs. Retrospective findings that identify process and tool misfits are direct evidence for Tailoring recalibration. The correct response: evaluate better-fit tools, pilot-transition, and document as a lessons learned item. This type of question connects specific project events to PMBOK 7 principles — an increasing PMP exam pattern.' },
  { domain:'Process', scenario:'A project manager has completed the risk identification workshop. The team identified 62 risks. The sponsor says: "62 risks is too many — reduce it to 20 maximum."', question:'What should the project manager do?', options:['Reduce the risk register to 20 risks as directed by the sponsor','Explain to the sponsor that risk count is determined by project complexity, not by arbitrary limit; the appropriate approach is to perform qualitative risk analysis to prioritize the 62 risks — high-priority risks get full treatment, lower-priority ones are monitored or accepted','Accept the 62 risks but only actively manage 20','Ask the team to merge similar risks until the total is 20'], correct:1, explanation:'Arbitrary risk count limits undermine risk management effectiveness. The sponsor\'s concern is likely about management overhead, not risk count per se. The PM\'s professional response: explain the prioritization process — qualitative analysis will identify the ~10-15 truly high-priority risks for active management, while others are on a watch list with lighter oversight. This gives the sponsor manageable focus without hiding risks from the register. Artificial consolidation or deletion of risks creates blind spots. This is advocating for professional risk management practices under organizational pressure.' },
  { domain:'Process', scenario:'A project team is planning an agile project. The stakeholders want a fixed end date (6 months) and a fixed feature set. The team says this is impossible given the uncertainty.', question:'What should the project manager recommend?', options:['Commit to fixed date and fixed features since stakeholders have the authority to set these constraints','Educate stakeholders on the agile iron triangle: in agile, either features or timeline must flex. Propose options: (1) fix the timeline with priority-ordered features (deliver what fits in 6 months), or (2) fix the features but with a variable timeline (deliver when done). Present risks of trying to fix both.','Convert to waterfall to be able to commit to both','Tell the team to work overtime to accommodate all constraints'], correct:1, explanation:'The Agile Iron Triangle explicitly cannot have all three constraints (scope, time, resources) fixed simultaneously in an uncertain environment — this is why agile was created. The PM\'s role is to educate stakeholders on the trade-off and present real options with their implications. Option 1 (fixed time, variable scope): "here\'s our best estimate of what 6 months delivers, with priority order ensuring the most valuable features are first." Option 2 (fixed scope, variable time): "here\'s when we estimate all features will be done with the given team size." Making the constraint trade-off explicit enables stakeholders to make an informed decision.' },
  { domain:'Process', scenario:'A construction project is 70% complete. A critical piece of equipment arrives damaged from the supplier. Replacing it will take 6 weeks, delaying the project significantly.', question:'What should the project manager do immediately?', options:['Accept the 6-week delay and update the schedule','Simultaneously: document the damage formally, file a warranty/insurance claim with the supplier, investigate all possible recovery options (expedited replacement, alternative equipment sources, renting substitutes, redesigning around the damage), update the risk register, and communicate impact to stakeholders with options','File an insurance claim and wait for resolution','Accelerate other project activities to compensate'], correct:1, explanation:'Equipment damage is a risk event requiring immediate multi-front response. Single-track thinking (wait for replacement) wastes the 6-week window. Parallel actions: (1) Document damage for legal/insurance purposes. (2) Explore ALL equipment recovery options simultaneously (expedited manufacturer replacement, used equipment markets, equipment rental, alternative equipment with design modification). (3) Assess which other project activities can proceed without the equipment. (4) Communicate honestly to stakeholders with options and their trade-offs. This is crisis risk management — proactive, parallel, option-generating.' },
  { domain:'Process', scenario:'An agile team is about to begin a new sprint. During sprint planning, the team discovers that 3 of 8 planned user stories have unclear acceptance criteria.', question:'What should happen?', options:['Include the stories with unclear criteria and clarify during development','Do not include stories with unclear acceptance criteria in the sprint commitment — they should be refined in the product backlog and added to a future sprint after clarification','Include the stories but flag them for PM review','Ask the Product Owner to write the acceptance criteria during the sprint'], correct:1, explanation:'Acceptance criteria define "done" for each user story — without them, the team cannot know when the work is complete or how to test it. Pulling unclear stories into a sprint creates ambiguity that leads to rework, extended sprints, and quality issues. The correct process: stories without clear acceptance criteria return to backlog refinement (not sprint ready). The Product Owner must clarify criteria before the next sprint planning session. This is the "Definition of Ready" concept — stories must be understood, estimable, and testable before entering a sprint. It protects both team velocity and product quality.' },
  { domain:'Process', scenario:'A project manager is developing the project management plan. The project involves 8 knowledge areas. Which subsidiary plan is developed FIRST?', question:'What is the correct order of developing subsidiary management plans?', options:['Cost Management Plan — because budget is the primary project constraint','The project management planning process begins with scope (Plan Scope Management) since scope defines what work is needed, which then enables resource, schedule, and cost planning. However, all subsidiary plans are developed iteratively and concurrently, not in strict sequence.','Risk Management Plan — because risks must be understood before planning can proceed','The order depends entirely on what the project sponsor prioritizes'], correct:1, explanation:'PMBOK doesn\'t mandate a strict sequence for subsidiary plan development (they interact and are developed iteratively), but logically scope comes first — you can\'t plan resources, schedule, or cost for undefined scope. In practice: Scope → defines Work → enables Resource → enables Schedule → enables Cost. Risk and quality planning happen simultaneously. Communications and stakeholder engagement plans can begin early. The exam may present this as a sequencing question — the key insight is that scope planning logically precedes most other planning because it defines the work being planned.' },
  { domain:'Process', scenario:'A project manager receives a change request to expand the project scope that would increase the budget by 15% and extend the timeline by 4 weeks. The CCB has approved the change.', question:'What must the project manager do NEXT?', options:['Implement the change immediately since CCB has approved it','Update the project management plan (scope baseline, schedule baseline, cost baseline), update all affected project documents, communicate the approved change to all stakeholders, and then implement the change according to the updated plan','Communicate the change to the team and begin implementation','Archive the CCB decision and continue without updating plan documents'], correct:1, explanation:'CCB approval is a trigger, not the end state. After approval, the PM must update ALL affected baselines: scope statement (add new scope), WBS (add new work packages), schedule (add time, adjust critical path), and cost baseline (add budget). Other documents that may need updating: risk register (new scope creates new risks), resource plan, communications plan. Stakeholder communication informs everyone who needs to know about the approved change. Only THEN does implementation begin — against the updated, re-baselined plan. Implementing against the old plan means performance measurement will be wrong.' },
  { domain:'Process', scenario:'A project manager is planning an infrastructure project that will take 18 months. The PM estimates that detailed planning of all activities for 18 months upfront is not feasible due to uncertainty in later phases.', question:'What planning technique is MOST appropriate?', options:['Complete all planning upfront regardless of uncertainty — it provides the most control','Use Rolling Wave Planning: plan near-term activities in detail (next 2-3 months), and plan future phases at a higher level of abstraction, progressively elaborating detail as the project approaches those phases','Skip planning for later phases entirely and figure them out during execution','Use a pure agile approach and plan only one sprint at a time'], correct:1, explanation:'Rolling Wave Planning is the standard PMBOK technique for managing planning uncertainty in longer-horizon projects. Near-term work is planned in sufficient detail for reliable execution. Future work is planned at a higher level (milestones, phase objectives) until enough information is available to elaborate. This is progressive elaboration applied to schedule planning. The approach provides control where it\'s needed (near term) while acknowledging uncertainty where it exists (long term). It\'s compatible with both waterfall (where phases define the waves) and agile (where sprints are the waves).' },
  { domain:'Process', scenario:'An agile project\'s Definition of Done requires code review, unit testing, integration testing, and documentation for every user story. A team member says the DoD is too heavy and slows them down.', question:'What should happen?', options:['Remove the components the team member finds burdensome to improve velocity','The team collectively owns the DoD — the team member should raise the concern in a retrospective where the whole team evaluates whether each DoD component adds genuine value. Changes to DoD require team consensus (and potentially stakeholder agreement), not individual preference.','The PM decides which DoD components to remove','Keep the DoD exactly as it is since changing it sets a bad precedent'], correct:1, explanation:'The Definition of Done is a team artifact, owned collectively. Individual members cannot unilaterally modify it. However, if a team member believes a component is waste (not adding quality value), this is a legitimate retrospective agenda item. The team evaluates: Does code review catch defects that unit tests miss? Does documentation serve downstream users? If YES, the component stays (it\'s creating value). If NO, the team can remove it by consensus. This is empirical process control — the team continuously improves their own working methods through structured reflection. Retrospectives are the proper forum; individual decisions are not.' },
  { domain:'Process', scenario:'During monitoring and controlling, a project manager identifies that the quality of deliverables has declined in the last three reporting periods. The root cause analysis indicates the team is rushing due to schedule pressure.', question:'What should the PM do?', options:['Reduce the quality requirements to match what the team can achieve under schedule pressure','Do not sacrifice quality for schedule. Instead, analyze the schedule pressure source, evaluate options (add resources, reduce scope, extend timeline), and present the trade-off to the sponsor — quality is not a lever to reduce in response to schedule pressure','Add more quality reviews to catch defects before delivery','Ask the team to work faster and more carefully simultaneously'], correct:1, explanation:'Quality-time trade-offs are a fundamental project management tension. PMI\'s position: quality is not a variable to be reduced. If quality is degrading due to schedule pressure, the PM must: address the root cause (unrealistic schedule), present the constraint trade-off to the sponsor (scope, time, quality, cost — something must give), and never silently reduce quality standards. The sponsor may authorize scope reduction, timeline extension, or additional resources — all legitimate responses. Reducing quality standards without stakeholder knowledge and approval is a governance failure. Adding more reviews after delivery is too late — it catches defects, not prevents them.' },
  { domain:'Process', scenario:'A project manager receives a deliverable from a vendor. The deliverable meets contractual requirements but the project team reports it has significant usability issues that will require extensive user training.', question:'What can the project manager do?', options:['Formally reject the deliverable since it doesn\'t meet the PM\'s expectations','Accept the deliverable per contract (it meets contractual specs), document the usability issues as lessons learned, update the risk register, ensure training budget and timeline are adjusted to accommodate the additional training needs, and consider including usability requirements explicitly in future contracts','Refuse payment to the vendor until usability issues are resolved','Ask the vendor to resolve usability issues at no charge since they built what was specified'], correct:1, explanation:'This scenario illustrates the gap between contractual compliance and actual fitness for use. The vendor met the contract — legally, acceptance is required. However: document the usability gap as a lessons learned item (usability requirements should have been in the contract), adjust the project plan to account for additional training needs (these are now known scope items), and update future procurement templates to include usability acceptance criteria. Refusing payment for contractual compliance creates legal liability. Demanding vendor fixes for items not in the contract is also legally unjustifiable. Prevention through better contract specification is the lesson.' },
  { domain:'Process', scenario:'A project manager is creating the stakeholder engagement plan. One powerful stakeholder group has been classified as "resistant" in the stakeholder engagement assessment.', question:'What should the engagement plan specify for resistant stakeholders?', options:['Minimize communication with resistant stakeholders to avoid conflict','Tailor engagement intensity to resistance: meet frequently, understand specific concerns, involve them in relevant decisions where possible, assign a sponsor or senior advocate to build relationship, and track their engagement level over time for movement toward neutral or supportive','Include them in standard communications only','Document their resistance and escalate to executive management for intervention'], correct:1, explanation:'Resistant stakeholders are among the most important to actively engage — they have the power to block or undermine the project. The engagement plan for resistant stakeholders should specify: higher-frequency bilateral communication, specific objection-addressing actions, involvement in decisions relevant to their interests (they become invested in outcomes they influence), and a sponsoring relationship from someone they respect. Monitoring movement on the engagement assessment matrix tracks effectiveness. Minimizing contact with powerful resistant stakeholders is the fastest path to project failure. This is proactive stakeholder management — a signature PMP exam topic.' },
  { domain:'Process', scenario:'A project manager discovers midway through the project that the initial requirements were collected only from the project sponsor and IT department, excluding end users who will use the deliverable daily.', question:'What should the PM do?', options:['Continue with existing requirements since the project is already 50% complete','Conduct a supplementary requirements elicitation session with end users immediately, assess whether discovered gaps or conflicts require scope changes, prioritize changes through the change control process, and update the stakeholder register to include end users as a formal stakeholder group','Add end users to the stakeholder register but do not re-elicit requirements at this stage','Document the omission and address it in the next project'], correct:1, explanation:'End-user exclusion from requirements is a significant quality and adoption risk. At 50% completion: re-elicitation is still valuable — discovering critical gaps now is far less expensive than post-deployment rework. The process: conduct focused end-user sessions (not comprehensive re-elicitation, but targeted validation), identify gaps, prioritize changes by impact and cost to incorporate at this stage, route significant changes through CCB. Some lower-priority gaps may be deferred to a subsequent release. Update the stakeholder register to formalize end users. This is managing discovery of stakeholder gaps mid-project — a practical scenario that tests requirements management knowledge.' },

// ─────────────────────────── BUSINESS ENVIRONMENT (~14 questions) ───────────────────────────
  { domain:'Business Environment', scenario:'An organization has a portfolio of 12 active projects. A new strategic priority has emerged requiring immediate investment. The portfolio manager asks PMs to identify which projects could be paused or terminated.', question:'What should a PM provide to support this decision?', options:['Resist providing information that could lead to their project\'s termination','Prepare an objective assessment of the project\'s current strategic alignment, remaining value to be delivered, termination cost, and impact of pausing vs. continuing — enabling portfolio leadership to make an informed prioritization decision','Provide only positive project data to maximize the chance the project continues','Ask the sponsor to advocate for the project to the portfolio manager'], correct:1, explanation:'Portfolio management is a strategic activity that serves organizational goals, not individual project continuity. A PM who provides objective termination analysis — even when it might recommend pausing their own project — demonstrates professional integrity and strategic maturity. This includes: current strategic relevance, percent complete, sunk vs. remaining investment, termination/pause cost, and what would be lost vs. saved. Advocacy for project continuation (option D) is legitimate but should be based on data, not positional protection. PMI\'s ethics code requires honesty in reporting.' },
  { domain:'Business Environment', scenario:'A regulatory body announces that new data privacy regulations will take effect in 8 months, affecting the data architecture of a software project currently in development. The project is due to complete in 10 months.', question:'What should the project manager do?', options:['Wait for the project to complete, then adjust for regulations in the next phase','Immediately assess the regulatory impact on the project architecture, initiate a change request for required modifications before the regulations take effect, and ensure the project delivery includes a compliant architecture within the original 10-month timeline — or negotiate timeline adjustment if compliance requires it','Deliver the current non-compliant architecture and create a separate compliance project','Have the legal team manage all regulatory compliance activities separately'], correct:1, explanation:'Regulatory compliance is a hard constraint — it is not optional. With 8 months until regulations take effect and 10 months until project completion, there is a narrow window to build compliance into the delivery. The PM must: analyze the specific regulatory requirements and their architectural implications, quantify the scope and cost of compliant redesign, submit a change request if scope/schedule/cost baselines are affected, and coordinate with the legal/compliance team. Delivering non-compliant architecture and fixing it in a subsequent project creates legal risk and guaranteed rework cost. Proactive compliance integration is the professional standard.' },
  { domain:'Business Environment', scenario:'A project manager is managing a project expected to deliver $5M in annual savings. The project has consumed $8M of its $10M budget and is expected to be completed within budget. However, market changes have reduced the expected savings to $1.5M annually.', question:'What should the project manager recommend?', options:['Complete the project since it is within budget and nearly done','Prepare an updated business case analysis: the NPV of $1.5M/year may no longer justify the remaining $2M investment plus implementation costs. Present the analysis to the sponsor with a recommendation on whether to continue, reduce scope, or terminate — factoring in strategic alignment and alternative uses of the remaining $2M.','Increase the project scope to find ways to recover the original $5M savings target','Report the situation in the next status report but make no recommendation'], correct:1, explanation:'Business case validity must be reassessed when conditions change. A project within budget but with dramatically reduced benefits may no longer justify completion from an ROI perspective. The PM\'s professional obligation: conduct an objective NPV re-analysis. If NPV is now negative (remaining $2M costs + implementation exceed $1.5M annual savings recovery period), termination or scope reduction may be the rational recommendation. The PM does not make the final decision (that\'s the sponsor/steering committee), but must ensure decision-makers have accurate, updated business case information. Completing a project that no longer makes business sense is organizational waste.' },
  { domain:'Business Environment', scenario:'An organization is implementing a new enterprise-wide change management methodology. A project manager on an existing project receives guidance to begin using the new methodology immediately, even though the project is 60% complete.', question:'What should the project manager do?', options:['Immediately switch to the new methodology for all remaining project work','Assess the impact of mid-project methodology change on team, processes, and deliverables. If the change creates significant disruption, present a case to the PMO for a phased adoption (apply new methodology from the start of the next project while completing this one under current approach), or if mandatory, plan the transition carefully with minimal disruption.','Ignore the new methodology guidance since the project predates it','Apply the new methodology only to new activities, keeping completed work under the old approach'], correct:1, explanation:'Mid-project methodology changes are high-disruption events. The PM must balance: organizational compliance with the new methodology mandate vs. project stability at 60% completion. Key considerations: how different is the new methodology? Would switching create rework, retraining, or governance disruption? The PM\'s advocacy position: complete this project under current methodology (which is 60% done and presumably functioning), start all new projects under the new methodology. If the switch is mandatory regardless, plan it carefully with team training, process documentation, and stakeholder communication. The PM\'s role is to manage the change impact, not simply comply or resist.' },
  { domain:'Business Environment', scenario:'A project manager is delivering a cybersecurity improvement project. During the project, the PM discovers evidence of an existing security breach in the client\'s system that is unrelated to the project\'s scope.', question:'What must the project manager do?', options:['Ignore it since it is outside the project scope','Immediately escalate the discovered breach to the appropriate authority within the client organization (CISO, security team, or equivalent), regardless of project scope boundaries — the PM has an ethical obligation to report security threats that could harm the organization or its customers','Document it in the project risk register and address it in a future project','Report it only if the client specifically asks whether such a breach has been discovered'], correct:1, explanation:'Cybersecurity breaches affecting organizational security and customer data have an ethical disclosure obligation that transcends project scope. PMI\'s Code of Ethics requires reporting threats to safety and security. In many jurisdictions (GDPR, HIPAA, etc.), there are also legal notification requirements. The PM must: immediately escalate to the appropriate security authority within the client organization (not wait, not include in project risk register), and document that the escalation occurred. Scope limitations do not override ethical and legal disclosure obligations. This is professional responsibility at the intersection of PM ethics and cybersecurity governance.' },
  { domain:'Business Environment', scenario:'A project manager is developing the benefits management plan. The project will deliver new training capabilities for 500 employees over 2 years.', question:'What should the benefits management plan include?', options:['Only the training content and delivery schedule','The benefit metrics (e.g., skill certification rate, productivity improvement, turnover reduction), measurement baseline, measurement timeline (when will benefits be measured and by whom?), target benefit owner in operations, assumptions that must hold for benefits to be realized, and risks to benefit realization', 'Only the financial ROI calculation','The training vendor selection criteria and contract terms'], correct:1, explanation:'Benefits management (PMBOK 7 and PMI\'s Benefits Realization Management framework) requires that benefit realization is planned explicitly, not assumed. A robust benefits plan covers: what specific, measurable outcomes are expected (skill certification rate, productivity metrics), the baseline before the project, measurement timing (30/90/180 days post-deployment), who is accountable in operations for realizing benefits (not the PM — they are usually off-project by then), conditions that must hold for benefits to materialize (leadership support, budget for practice), and risks to realization. The plan creates accountability for outcomes, not just delivery of training.' },
  { domain:'Business Environment', scenario:'A project manager is asked to assess the feasibility of a proposed project. The initial estimate is $2M cost, 18-month timeline, with an expected NPV of $4M over 5 years. The risk assessment indicates high technical uncertainty.', question:'What should the feasibility assessment include beyond the financial analysis?', options:['Financial analysis (NPV) is sufficient for feasibility decision','A comprehensive feasibility assessment includes: technical feasibility (does the required technology exist/can it be built?), resource feasibility (does the organization have the skills and capacity?), market feasibility (will the expected demand materialize?), organizational feasibility (will the culture support this change?), schedule feasibility (is 18 months realistic?), and risk assessment — with the high technical uncertainty explicitly quantified in the NPV range (best/worst case)','Only organizational readiness beyond financials','Only risk assessment in addition to financial analysis'], correct:1, explanation:'Feasibility analysis is multidimensional. A positive NPV means nothing if the organization lacks technical capability to build the solution, doesn\'t have the talent to staff the project, or the culture will resist adoption. High technical uncertainty (the scenario\'s red flag) means the $4M NPV has a very wide confidence interval — the actual NPV could be negative if technical challenges are greater than expected. A professional feasibility assessment presents a range: "if technical challenges are resolved by month 6, NPV = $4M; if they take 12 months, NPV = $1.5M; if unresolvable, NPV = −$2M." This enables informed go/no-go decision-making.' },
  { domain:'Business Environment', scenario:'A government project manager is under pressure to award a subcontract to a vendor that is owned by a close relative of the project\'s executive sponsor. The sponsor has not disclosed this relationship.', question:'What should the project manager do?', options:['Award the contract if the vendor\'s technical proposal scores highest on the evaluation criteria','Independently verify the relationship allegation, refuse to participate in the procurement process without formal disclosure of the conflict of interest, escalate to the organization\'s ethics officer or procurement oversight function, and document all actions taken','Award the contract to a different vendor without explanation to avoid conflict','Ignore the concern since the sponsor has not formally disclosed a conflict'], correct:1, explanation:'Undisclosed conflicts of interest in procurement are serious governance violations and potentially illegal in government contracting. The PM has both an ethical and legal obligation to: verify the alleged relationship, refuse to process the procurement without proper disclosure, escalate to ethics oversight (Inspector General in government context), and document all steps. Awarding to the highest-scoring vendor does not resolve the conflict of interest — the selection process itself is compromised if undisclosed relationships affected how proposals were evaluated. Documenting actions protects the PM from later accountability. PMI\'s ethics code makes conflict of interest management explicit.' },
  { domain:'Business Environment', scenario:'A project manager receives a project brief from the sponsor containing very ambitious business objectives (increase market share by 30% in 12 months) with a modest project budget of $800K.', question:'What should the project manager do before accepting the charter?', options:['Accept the charter and deliver against the stated objectives','Conduct a preliminary gap analysis: Are the $800K budget and 12-month timeline realistic to achieve 30% market share growth? Present an evidence-based assessment of what the proposed investment can realistically deliver, and negotiate realistic objectives or additional resources before formally accepting','Accept the charter but communicate informally that objectives are unrealistic','Begin the project and revise objectives down when the reality of the constraint becomes clear during execution'], correct:1, explanation:'Accepting an unachievable charter sets the project up for failure and the PM up for accountability they cannot meet. Before the charter is signed, the PM must assess feasibility: "What can $800K and 12 months realistically deliver in terms of market share improvement?" If the analysis shows a 5-10% realistic improvement, the PM must present this to the sponsor and negotiate either: more realistic objectives (5-10% target), additional investment ($3M for 30% target), or a phased approach. Accepting and then revising down during execution damages trust and creates accountability problems. This is pre-charter negotiation of realistic scope — a governance best practice.' },
  { domain:'Business Environment', scenario:'A portfolio of technology projects is consuming 80% of the IT department\'s capacity. A strategic analysis shows that 40% of those projects have low strategic alignment but are consuming significant resources.', question:'What recommendation should the PM/portfolio manager make?', options:['Continue all projects since they were approved through proper governance','Recommend a portfolio rationalization review to the executive leadership: terminate or defer low-strategic-value projects to free capacity for higher-value work, and establish ongoing portfolio health reviews to prevent accumulation of low-value work','Request additional IT capacity to handle all current projects simultaneously','Let all projects complete and implement new strategic prioritization only for new projects'], correct:1, explanation:'Portfolio management exists to maximize strategic value from limited resources. If 40% of projects have low strategic alignment and are consuming 32% of IT capacity (40% × 80%), that capacity could deliver significantly more value if redirected. The PM/Portfolio Manager recommendation: (1) transparent assessment of each project\'s strategic alignment score and remaining value, (2) portfolio rationalization review with leadership, (3) orderly termination or deferment of low-value projects (not immediate shutdown — proper closure), (4) establish portfolio health review cadence. This reflects PMBOK 7 Principle #4 (Focus on Value) at the portfolio level.' },
  { domain:'Business Environment', scenario:'A project is creating a product for the consumer market. Market research shows that competitors will likely release a similar product 3 months before the current project schedule predicts delivery.', question:'What options should the project manager present to the sponsor?', options:['Continue the project as planned since market timing is an external factor beyond project control','Present three options: (1) Accelerate to market with reduced scope (MVP approach — release the 3 most critical features 3 months early and follow with the full feature set), (2) Reposition the product to compete on differentiation rather than timing (adjust scope to add unique features competitors won\'t have), (3) Assess whether a partnership or acquisition could accelerate time-to-market. Each option with trade-off analysis.','Terminate the project since the competitive advantage is lost','Add resources immediately to compress the schedule by 3 months'], correct:1, explanation:'Competitive market changes are strategic risks that the PM must surface and respond to with options. Three viable strategic responses exist: (1) Speed to market — MVP approach delivers partial product faster, capturing early adopters; (2) Differentiation — if you can\'t be first, be better (add unique capabilities competitors won\'t have for 12 months); (3) Partnership/acquisition — strategic options to leapfrog the competitive gap. Adding resources (option D) is a tactical schedule response that doesn\'t address the competitive dynamics. Continuing unchanged (option A) ignores a significant business risk. The PM\'s role is to present strategic options with trade-offs, not make the strategy call unilaterally.' },
  { domain:'Business Environment', scenario:'A project manager is planning a project in a country with a different language, and the primary project deliverables will be used by speakers of that language.', question:'What should the project manager include in the project plan to address language requirements?', options:['Deliver all documentation in the PM\'s native language since it is the international business standard','Include translation and localization as explicit project deliverables in the WBS, budget for professional translation services, include native-language user acceptance testing, and identify bilingual team members or translators as required resources','Provide English documentation with a note that local translation is the client\'s responsibility','Use automated translation tools to convert documentation at project close'], correct:1, explanation:'Language localization is a legitimate scope requirement if the deliverables will be used by non-native speakers. "Localization" goes beyond word-for-word translation: it includes cultural adaptation of terminology, date/currency formats, UI text strings, and user documentation. These are real deliverables with associated cost, time, and quality requirements that must be planned explicitly — not treated as an afterthought. Automated translation for professional documents (technical specifications, legal agreements, user manuals) is generally insufficient quality. End-user acceptance testing in the target language is critical for usability validation.' },
  { domain:'Business Environment', scenario:'A project sponsor informs the project manager that the organization\'s board of directors has decided to divest the business unit that owns this project. The project has 4 months remaining until completion.', question:'What should the project manager do?', options:['Continue the project normally since the divestiture hasn\'t happened yet','Immediately raise the strategic uncertainty with the sponsor: does the new owner (post-divestiture) intend to continue the project? Assess transition risk, begin documenting project status and knowledge transfer materials, and potentially accelerate closure of key milestones to maximize value delivered before ownership transfer.','Terminate the project immediately to avoid complications','Wait for formal divestiture announcement before taking any action'], correct:1, explanation:'A divestiture creates fundamental strategic uncertainty for projects within the affected business unit. The PM\'s responsibilities: (1) Understand the likely ownership transition and whether the new owner supports project continuation. (2) Assess transition risk — will project team, systems, and vendor contracts survive the transition? (3) Prepare comprehensive documentation of project status, decisions, and remaining work so knowledge is not lost in the transition. (4) Consider whether accelerating key milestone delivery (pre-divestiture) protects value. This is organizational change management at the portfolio level — the PM must be proactive, not passive, about strategic uncertainty.' },
];
